04264nam a22005295i 9780774815222DE-B159720240306124542.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20092008xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97807748152227 a10.59962/97807748152222doi  a(DE-B1597)662281  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 4aHQ728 ǂb D2413 2008eb 7aSOC0260102bisacsh04a306.851 aDagenais, Daniel, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut13aLa fin de la famille moderne /cDaniel Dagenais. 1aVancouver ;aToronto : bUniversity of British Columbia Press, c[2009] 4c©2008  a1 online resource (512 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFront Matter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- tThe Ideal Type of the Modern Family -- tFamily Ties: The Domain of Kinship -- tThe Question of Private and Public Spheres -- tThe Parental Role -- tGender, Gender Differences, and Sexuality -- tThe Conjugal Relationship -- tThe French-Canadian Family -- tContemporary Changes in the Family: What Do They Mean? -- tEpilogue -- tAfterword -- tNotes -- tReferences -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe family institution is undergoing a radical transformation. The modern meanings of kinship, marriage, parenthood, gender, and sexuality are now being questioned, and debates on same-sex marriages and parenthood or on divorce and blended families are reflective of these challenges. The (Un)Making of the Modern Family is neither an indictment of the new family nor a rallying cry. It is a classical exercise of family sociology that draws upon a range of disciplines -- history, anthropology, psychology, and demography -- to provide an interpretive model for understanding contemporary changes in the family. It explores traditional family forms in order to identify changes that gave birth to the ideal type of the modern family, and it discusses how the modern family's constituent elements (the family as institution, conjugal and parent-child relationships, and gender and sexuality) relate to modernity's central feature -- the concept of the individual. By reconstructing an archetype of the modern family, this book explains why individuals have experienced its deconstruction as a profound identity crisis. It will appeal to anyone concerned with the future of the (post)modern family and society. Published originally by Les Presses de l'Universit� Laval as La fin de la famille moderne, this book was awarded the 2000-1 Prix Jean-Charles Falardeau for the best book published in French in Canada in the field of social sciences.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Sociology / Marriage & Family.2bisacsh1 aBrierley, Jane, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package Pre-2010z978311127416408iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package pre 2010z978311127724008iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of British Columbia eBook-Package 2013-2000z978311141860540uhttps://doi.org/10.59962/978077481522240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780774815222423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780774815222/original  a978-3-11-127416-4  ACUP Complete eBook-Package Pre-2010b2010  a978-3-11-127724-0  ACUP Upgrade eBook-Package pre 2010b2010  a978-3-11-141860-5  University of British Columbia eBook-Package 2013-2000c2013d2000  aGBV-deGruyter-alles